Just FYI, if you submit changes through Gerrit they will be merged into the code base. We don't need to abandon reviews and commit directly any longer.
Thanks Steffen. I was aware of that but needed to rebase first. Is it possible to rebase via Gerrit directly?

Unfortunately the version of Gerrit that is currently deployed does not support that directly. An update to Gerrit 2.4 which supports rebasing is planned but the webmasters ran into some issues (bug 377123) so the upgrade was postponed.
So what is the best/recommended way to do this? My local rebase/commit/push was intended to achieve the desired result with fewer steps - but of course had the downside of abandoning the review.
BTW, I would also like to abandon https://git.eclipse.org/r/#change,6540 since it's now obsolete but don't have permissions to do that.

I believe only the submitter can abandon reviews. I'm not sure why committers don't have super powers for that but Gerrit seems to be configured that way. I would recommend raising a bug in Community/Gerrit to request that.
If you push the rebased change to "ssh://git.eclipse.org:29418/mylyn/org.eclipse.mylyn.tasks refs/head/master" the review would be automatically closed but I don't think the Eclipse.org setup allows pushing directly to master. It's something that we should consider requesting as well.
Currently you have to push the rebased change to refs/for/master and then approve and submit through the web UI.

Thanks Steffen, I've created bug 386146 requesting the change to Gerrit.
Why would pusing a rebased change automatically close a review? Unless I'm missing something isn't it a common use case to rebase a review that is still in the works? Perhaps we should move this discussion to the mailing list.

(In reply to comment #19) > Why would pusing a rebased change automatically close a review?
If you push the commit to the destination branch Gerrit recognizes that the review was merged and automatically closes the review. It's essentially just a different workflow for submitting a review.
> Unless I'm > missing something isn't it a common use case to rebase a review that is still in > the works?
I avoid that until a change has been fully reviewed and approved. If you rebase while iterating it becomes much more difficult to compare patch sets since the diff will contain unrelated changes.
